SIMPLE: symbol
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Symbol
<hw>Sym"bol</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧m"b⟦ocr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>symbolus</ets>, <ets>symbolum</ets>, Gr. <grk>sy`mbolon</grk> a
sign by which one knows or infers a thing, from <grk>symba`llein</grk>
to throw or put together, to compare; <grk>sy`n</grk> with +
<grk>ba`llein</grk> to throw: cf. F. <ets>symbole</ets>. Cf.
<er>Emblem</er>, <er>Parable</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A visible
sign or representation of an idea; anything which suggests an idea or
quality, or another thing, as by resemblance or by convention; an
emblem; a representation; a type; a figure; <as>as, the lion is the
<ex>symbol</ex> of courage; the lamb is the <ex>symbol</ex> of meekness
or patience</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>symbol</qex> is a sign included in the idea which it
represents, <it>e. g.</it>, an actual part chosen to represent the
whole, or a lower form or species used as the representative of a higher
in the same kind.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Any character used to represent a
quantity, an operation, a relation, or an abbreviation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In crystallography, the <xex>symbol</xex> of a plane is
the numerical expression which defines its position relatively to the
assumed axes.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>An abstract or compendium of
faith or doctrine; a creed, or a summary of the articles of
religion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[Gr. <?/ contributions.]</ety> <def>That which is
thrown into a common fund; hence, an appointed or accustomed duty.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They do their work in the days of peace . . . and come to pay
their <qex>symbol</qex> in a war or in a plague.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Share; allotment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The persons who are to be judged . . . shall all appear to receive
their <qex>symbol</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An abbreviation standing for the
name of an element and consisting of the initial letter of the Latin or
New Latin name, or sometimes of the initial letter with a following one;
<as>as, <chform>C</chform> for carbon, <chform>Na</chform> for sodium
(Natrium), <chform>Fe</chform> for iron (Ferrum), <chform>Sn</chform>
for tin (Stannum), <chform>Sb</chform> for antimony (Stibium), etc.</as>
See the list of names and symbols under <er>Element</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In pure and organic chemistry there are symbols not only
for the elements, but also for their grouping in formulas, radicals, or
residues, as evidenced by their composition, reactions, synthesis, etc.
See the diagram of <cref>Benzene nucleus</cref>, under
<er>Benzene</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Emblem; figure; type. See
<er>Emblem</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Symbol</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Symbol
<hw>Sym"bol</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To symbolize.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Symbolic</ent>⟦br⟧
